one night, but the brothers kept waking me up

to look at the ring around the moon . . . did you

go to the Toga party? ... yeah, that was the night

Bob Etter boots one of his three

field goals against Michigan

34 yards.

Ridlehuber pulls the Michigan defense one

way, turns and goes the other way for 22

yards, setting up a Georgia touchdown.

Jimmy Cooley blocks a Clemson punt; Larry Kohn grabs

it at the 2 and falls into the end zone for the touchdown.

Georgia fools the Clemson secondary on a

tricky 34-yard pass play: Ridlehuber to

Taylor, back to Ridlehuber, and on to

Hodgson for the touchdown.

After Billy Cloers miracle recovery

of Crawfords onsides kick late in

the fourth quarter at Chapel Hill,

Ridlehuber races 31 yards to score

the winning touchdown.

Georgia scores on a pass from

Moore to Hodgson in the fourth

quarter to take the lead against

Florida, 10-7.

Moore passes to Wheeler

against Auburn for the longest

touchdown pass in SEC history.

Tech's Kim King, hit by Patton, loses the ball. Glass recovers to set the stage for Georgias first TD.

A Tech pass is intercepted by Lynn Hughes . .

who runs for 25 yards to set up Georgias second score, a field goal by Bob Etter.

By way of ten field goals

and sixteen extra points,

junior Bob Etter led the

SEC in number of field

goals and scored more total

points than any other SEC

kicker.

Georgia suffered a great

loss in the Florida State

game when Bob Taylor, star

halfback from LaG range,

broke his leg and was lost

for remainder of his col-

lege football career.

Preston Ridlehuber never lost to

Tech when he was at the helm.

He lead the Bullpups to an 18-0

victory in 1962 and the Dogs to

7-0 and 17-7 triumphs in 1964

and 1965. This year he led the

SEC in average yards per punt

return, 21.9.

Lynn Hughes tied with three

other players in the SEC for

number of interceptions but

had the best average per inter-

ception, 17.5 yards.
